# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acetylene
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acetylene/1-4-butynediol] Several patented production methods use copper bismuth catalysts coated on an inert material.
[src:acetylene/1-4-butynediol] The normal temperature range for the reaction is 90 °C up to 150 °C, depending on the pressure used for the reaction which can range from 1 to 20 bar.
[src:acetylene/1-4-butynediol] 1,4-Butynediol is a precursor to 1,4-butanediol and 2-butene-1,4-diol by hydrogenation.
[src:acetylene/1-4-butynediol] It is also used in the manufacture of certain herbicides, textile additives, corrosion inhibitors, plasticizers, synthetic resins, and polyurethanes.
[src:acetylene/1-4-butynediol] It is the major raw material used in the synthesis of vitamin B6.
[src:acetylene/1-4-butynediol] It is also used for brightening, preserving, and inhibiting nickel plating.
[src:acetylene/1-4-butynediol] It reacts with a mixture of chlorine and hydrochloric acid to give mucochloric acid (HO2CC(Cl)=C(Cl)CHO).
[src:acetylene/1-4-butynediol] 1,4-Butynediol is corrosive and irritates the skin, eyes, and respiratory tract.
[src:acetylene/1-butyne] 1-Butyne participates in reactions typical for terminal alkynes, such as alkyne metathesis, hydrogenation, condensation with formaldehyde.
[src:acetylene/1-butyne] Based on its heat of combustion, it is slightly more stable than its isomer 2-butyne.
[src:acetylene/1-butyne] The combustion of 1-Butyne produces propargyl radicals, a precursor to soot and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, as the propargyl radicals can form basic aromatic rings, making butyne's fuel usage a concern for emissions.
[src:acetylene/1-butyne] 1-Butyne is in unsaturated C4 petroleum cuts, and has to be separated out in industrial hydrorefining to make 1-butene, which is used to make low density polyethylene and polybutene.
[src:acetylene/1-butyne] Distillation is impractical due to similar boiling points, so 1-butyne is removed by catalytic hydrogenation.
[src:acetylene/1-butyne] Usually the catalyst is palladium, operated with liquid hydrocarbon and hydrogen gas at 20-60°C and pressures up to 10 bar.
[src:acetylene/1-decyne] Under the catalysis of platinum, it reacts with hydrogen to produce decane.
[src:acetylene/1-hexyne] Its reactivity illustrates the behavior of terminal alkylacetylenes.
[src:acetylene/1-hexyne] The hexyl derivative is common test substrate because it is conveniently volatile.
[src:acetylene/1-hexyne] This reaction allows alkylation at the 3-position.
[src:acetylene/1-hexyne] Catechol borane adds to 1-hexyne to give the 1-hexenyl borane.
[src:acetylene/1-hexyne] 1-Hexyne reacts with diethyl fumarate to produce *n*-hexylsuccinic acid.
[src:acetylene/2-butyne] 2-Butyne is of interest to physical chemists because of its very low torsional barrier and the problem of determining that barrier using high-resolution infrared spectroscopy.
[src:acetylene/2-butyne] Analysis of its infrared spectrum leads to a determination that the torsional barrier is only 6 cm−1 (1.2×10−22 J or 72 J mol−1).
[src:acetylene/2-butyne] However, it has not been determined whether the equilibrium structure is eclipsed (D3h) or staggered (D3d).
[src:acetylene/2-butyne] Symmetry analysis using the Molecular Symmetry Group G36 shows that one would need to analyse its high resolution rotation-vibration Raman spectrum to determine its equilibrium structure.
[src:acetylene/2-butyne] Pulsed-field-ionisation zero-kinetic-energy (PFI-ZEKE) photoelectron spectra of 2-butyne and its fully deuterated isotopomer have been recorded and analysed.
[src:acetylene/2-butyne] 2-Butyne (*dimethylethyne*) forms with 5-decyne (*dibutylethyne*), 4-octyne (*dipropylethyne*) and 3-hexyne (*diethylethyne*) a group of symmetric alkynes.
[src:acetylene/2-butyne] 2-Butyne can be synthesized by the rearrangement reaction of ethylacetylene in a solution of ethanolic potassium hydroxide.
[src:acetylene/2-butyne] 2-Butyne, along with propyne, is used to synthesize alkylated hydroquinones in the total synthesis of Vitamin E.
[src:acetylene/2-hexyne] 2-Hexyne can be semihydrogenated to yield 2-hexene or fully hydrogenated to hexane.
[src:acetylene/2-hexyne] With appropriate noble metal catalysts it can selectively form *cis*-2-hexene.
[src:acetylene/2-hexyne] 2-Hexyne can act as a ligand on gold atoms.
[src:acetylene/2-hexyne] With strong sulfuric acid, the ketone 2-hexanone is produced.
[src:acetylene/2-hexyne] However this reaction also causes polymerization and charring.
[src:acetylene/2-hexyne] Under heat and pressure 2-hexyne polymerizes to linear oligomers and polymers.
[src:acetylene/2-hexyne] This can be hastened by some catalysts such as molybdenum pentachloride with tetraphenyl tin.
[src:acetylene/2-hexyne] However Ziegler–Natta catalysts have no action as the triple bond is hindered.
[src:acetylene/2-octyne] It is formed by isomerization of 1-octyne catalyzed by a YbII complex.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] As an alkyne, acetylene is unsaturated because its two carbon atoms are bonded together in a triple bond.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The carbon–carbon triple bond places all four atoms in the same straight line, with CCH bond angles of 180°.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The triple bond in acetylene results in a high energy content that is released when acetylene is burned.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene was discovered in 1836 by Edmund Davy, who identified it as a "new carburet of hydrogen".
[src:acetylene/acetylene] It was an accidental discovery while attempting to isolate potassium metal.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] By heating potassium carbonate with carbon at very high temperatures, he produced a residue of what is now known as potassium carbide, (K2C2), which reacted with water to release the new gas.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] It was rediscovered in 1860 by French chemist Marcellin Berthelot, who coined the name *acétylène*.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Berthelot's empirical formula for acetylene (C4H2), as well as the alternative name "*quadricarbure d'hydrogène*" (hydrogen quadricarbide), were incorrect because many chemists at that time used the wrong atomic mass for carbon (6 instead of 12).
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Berthelot was able to prepare this gas by passing vapours of organic compounds (methanol, ethanol, etc.) through a red hot tube and collecting the effluent.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] He also found that acetylene was formed by sparking electricity through mixed cyanogen and hydrogen gases.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Berthelot later obtained acetylene directly by passing hydrogen between the poles of a carbon arc.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] It is a recovered side product in production of ethylene by cracking of hydrocarbons.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Approximately 400,000 tonnes were produced by this method in 1983.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Its presence in ethylene is usually undesirable because of its explosive character and its ability to poison Ziegler–Natta catalysts.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] It is selectively hydrogenated into ethylene, usually using Pd–Ag catalysts.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] This last reaction is implemented in the process of anaerobic decomposition of methane by microwave plasma.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The first sample of acetylene produced was by Edmund Davy in 1836, via hydrolysis (decomposition using water) of potassium carbide.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] This reaction was discovered by Friedrich Wöhler in 1862, but a suitable commercial scale production method which allowed acetylene to be put into wider scale use was not found until 1892 by the Canadian inventor Thomas Willson while searching for a viable commercial production method for aluminum.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] As late as the early 21st century, China, Japan, and Eastern Europe produced acetylene primarily by this method.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The use of this technology has since declined worldwide with the notable exception of China, with its emphasis on coal-based chemical industry, as of 2013.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Otherwise oil has increasingly supplanted coal as the chief source of reduced carbon.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Calcium carbide production requires high temperatures, ~2000 °C, necessitating the use of an electric arc furnace.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] In the US, this process was an important part of the late-19th century revolution in chemistry enabled by the massive hydroelectric power project at Niagara Falls.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] In terms of valence bond theory, in each carbon atom the 2s orbital hybridizes with one 2p orbital thus forming an sp hybrid.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The other two 2p orbitals remain unhybridized.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The two ends of the two sp hybrid orbital overlap to form a strong σ valence bond between the carbons, while on each of the other two ends hydrogen atoms attach also by σ bonds.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The two unchanged 2p orbitals form a pair of weaker π bonds.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Since acetylene is a linear symmetrical molecule, it possesses the D∞h point group.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] At atmospheric pressure, acetylene cannot exist as a liquid and does not have a melting point.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The triple point on the phase diagram corresponds to the melting point (−80.8 °C) at the minimal pressure at which liquid acetylene can exist (1.27 atm).
[src:acetylene/acetylene] At temperatures below the triple point, solid acetylene can change directly to the vapour (gas) by sublimation.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The sublimation point at atmospheric pressure is −84.0 °C.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] At room temperature and atmospheric pressure, the solubility of acetylene in acetone is 27.9 g per kg.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] For the same amount of dimethylformamide (DMF), the solubility is 51 g.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] At 20.26 bar, the solubility increases to 689.0 and 628.0 g for acetone and DMF, respectively.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] These solvents are used in pressurized gas cylinders.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Approximately 20% of acetylene is supplied by the industrial gases industry for oxyacetylene gas welding and cutting due to the high temperature of the flame.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Combustion of acetylene with oxygen produces a flame of over 3,600 K (3,330 °C; 6,020 °F), releasing 11.8 kJ/g.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Oxygen with acetylene is the hottest burning common gas mixture.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Oxy-acetylene welding was a popular welding process in previous decades.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The development and advantages of arc-based welding processes have made oxy-fuel welding nearly extinct for many applications.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene usage for welding has dropped significantly.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Bell Canada cable-repair technicians still use portable acetylene-fuelled torch kits as a soldering tool for sealing lead sleeve splices in manholes and in some aerial locations.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Oxyacetylene welding may also be used in areas where electricity is not readily accessible.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Oxyacetylene cutting is used in many metal fabrication shops.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] For use in welding and cutting, the working pressures must be controlled by a regulator, since above 15 psi (100 kPa), if subjected to a shockwave (caused, for example, by a flashback), acetylene decomposes explosively into hydrogen and carbon.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene is useful for many processes, but few are conducted on a commercial scale.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] One of the major chemical applications is ethynylation of formaldehyde.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The reaction gives butynediol, with propargyl alcohol as the by-product.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Copper acetylide is used as the catalyst.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] In addition to ethynylation, acetylene reacts with carbon monoxide to give acrylic acid, or acrylic esters.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] These derivatives form products such as acrylic fibers, glasses, paints, resins, and polymers.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Except in China, use of acetylene as a chemical feedstock has declined by 70% from 1965 to 2007 owing to cost and environmental considerations.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] In China, acetylene is a major precursor to vinyl chloride.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Prior to the widespread use of petrochemicals, coal-derived acetylene was a building block for several industrial chemicals.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Thus acetylene can be hydrated to give acetaldehyde, which in turn can be oxidized to acetic acid.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Processes leading to acrylates were also commercialized.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Almost all of these processes became obsolete with the availability of petroleum-derived ethylene and propylene.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] In 1881, the Russian chemist Mikhail Kucherov described the hydration of acetylene to acetaldehyde using catalysts such as mercury(II) bromide.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Before the advent of the Wacker process, this reaction was conducted on an industrial scale.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The polymerization of acetylene with Ziegler–Natta catalysts produces polyacetylene films.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Polyacetylene, a chain of CH centres with alternating single and double bonds, was one of the first discovered organic semiconductors.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Its reaction with iodine produces a highly electrically conducting material.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Although such materials are not useful, these discoveries led to the developments of organic semiconductors, as recognized by the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2000 to Alan J.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Heeger, Alan G MacDiarmid, and Hideki Shirakawa.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] In the 1920s, pure acetylene was experimentally used as an inhalation anesthetic.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene is sometimes used for carburization (that is, hardening) of steel when the object is too large to fit into a furnace.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene is used to volatilize carbon in radiocarbon dating.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The carbonaceous material in an archeological sample is treated with lithium metal in a small specialized research furnace to form lithium carbide (also known as lithium acetylide).
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The carbide can then be reacted with water, as usual, to form acetylene gas to feed into a mass spectrometer to measure the isotopic ratio of carbon-14 to carbon-12.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene combustion produces a strong, bright light and the ubiquity of carbide lamps drove much acetylene commercialization in the early 20th century.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Common applications included coastal lighthouses, street lights, and automobile and mining headlamps.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] In most of these applications, direct combustion is a fire hazard, and so acetylene has been replaced, first by incandescent lighting and many years later by low-power/high-lumen LEDs.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Nevertheless, acetylene lamps remain in limited use in remote or otherwise inaccessible areas and in countries with a weak or unreliable central electric grid.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The energy richness of the C≡C triple bond and the rather high solubility of acetylene in water make it a suitable substrate for bacteria, provided an adequate source is available.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] A number of bacteria living on acetylene have been identified.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene is a moderately common chemical in the universe, often associated with the atmospheres of gas giants.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] One curious discovery of acetylene is on Enceladus, a moon of Saturn.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Natural acetylene is believed to form from catalytic decomposition of long-chain hydrocarbons at temperatures of 1,700 K (1,430 °C; 2,600 °F) and above.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Since such temperatures are highly unlikely on such a small distant body, this discovery is potentially suggestive of catalytic reactions within that moon, making it a promising site to search for prebiotic chemistry.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] In vinylation reactions, H−X compounds add across the triple bond.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Alcohols and phenols add to acetylene to give vinyl ethers.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Similarly, vinylpyrrolidone and vinylcarbazole are produced industrially by vinylation of 2-pyrrolidone and carbazole.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The hydration of acetylene is a vinylation reaction, but the resulting vinyl alcohol isomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The reaction is catalyzed by mercury salts.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] This reaction once was the dominant technology for acetaldehyde production, but it has been displaced by the Wacker process, which affords acetaldehyde by oxidation of ethylene, a cheaper feedstock.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] A similar situation applies to the conversion of acetylene to the valuable vinyl chloride by hydrochlorination versus the oxychlorination of ethylene.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Vinyl acetate is used instead of acetylene for some vinylations, which are more accurately described as transvinylations.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Higher esters of vinyl acetate have been used in the synthesis of vinyl formate.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene and its derivatives (2-butyne, diphenylacetylene, etc.) form complexes with transition metals.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Its bonding to the metal is somewhat similar to that of ethylene complexes.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Metal acetylides, species of the formula L*n*M−C2R, are also common.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Copper(I) acetylide and silver acetylide can be formed in aqueous solutions with ease due to a favorable solubility equilibrium.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Various organometallic and inorganic reagents are effective.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene can be semihydrogenated to ethylene, providing a feedstock for a variety of polyethylene plastics.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene is not especially toxic, but when generated from calcium carbide, or CaC2, it can contain toxic impurities such as traces of phosphine and arsine, which gives it a distinct garlic-like smell.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] It is also highly flammable, as are most light hydrocarbons, hence its use in welding.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Although it is stable at normal pressures and temperatures, if it is subjected to pressures as low as 15 psig it can explode.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] The safe limit for acetylene therefore is 101 kPagage, or 15 psig.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Additionally, if acetylene is initiated by intense heat or a shockwave, it can decompose explosively if the absolute pressure of the gas exceeds about 200 kilopascals (29 psi).
[src:acetylene/acetylene] It is therefore supplied and stored dissolved in acetone or dimethylformamide (DMF), contained in a gas cylinder with a porous filling, which renders it safe to transport and use, given proper handling.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should be used in the upright position to avoid withdrawing acetone during use.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Information on safe storage of acetylene in upright cylinders is provided by the OSHA, Compressed Gas Association, United States Mine Safety and Health Administration (MSHA), EIGA, and other agencies.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Copper catalyses the decomposition of acetylene, and as a result acetylene should not be transported in copper pipes.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Cylinders should be stored in an area segregated from oxidizers to avoid exacerbated reaction in case of fire/leakage.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should not be stored in confined spaces, enclosed vehicles, garages, and buildings, to avoid unintended leakage leading to explosive atmosphere.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] In the US, National Electric Code (NEC) requires consideration for hazardous areas including those where acetylene may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Consideration may include electrical classification and use of listed Group A electrical components in US.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] Further information on determining the areas requiring special consideration is in NFPA 497.
[src:acetylene/acetylene] In Europe, ATEX also requires consideration for hazardous areas where flammable gases may be released during accidents or leaks.
